Incident.Summary: TWO VEHICLE HEAD ON MVC RESULTS IN A DUI/DWI ARREST AND POSSESSION OF CDS NOT MARIJUANA. DUI # 23-132: COTTER, JAMIE LEE

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: Maryland State Police Bel Air Barrack D-30 is equipped with mobile recording device Incident was captured on mobile recording device and BWC Defendant: Cotter, Jamie Lee Date of Birth: 10-18-1988 Date of Arrest: 05/20/2023 Time of Arrest: 2046 hours PA OLN: 31959052 DUI # 23-132 (Bel Air) TRAINING/CERTIFICATES: I am trained by the Maryland State Police and National Highway Traffic Safety Administration to administer standardized field sobriety test. I am a NHTSA certified SFST Instructor. I am trained by the Maryland State Police and NHTSA in ARIDE. I am certified by the NHTSA/IACP as a Drug Recognition Expert (DRE). I am certified by the IACP as a DRE Instructor I attended the 2019 DUI Conference in Ocean City, Maryland. I attended the 2022 Maryland DRE Conference in Ocean City, Maryland. I have completed the Cannabis intoxication/impairment workshop hosted by Montgomery County Police Department. I have been a guest instructor at the Cannabis intoxication/impairment workshop hosted by Montgomery County Police for States Attorneys. I am a certified LIDAR/RADAR operator through the Maryland State Police. I am certified as a Preliminary Breath Test Operator through the Maryland State Police. I am certified by the Maryland State Police as a License Plate Recognition operator. VEHICLE IN MOTION (PHASE 1) On 05/20/2023 at approximately 2020 hours, I (TFC Mott #6918) was dispatched to the area of 2813 Conowingo rd in Bel Air Maryland for the report of a two vehicle injury collision. As I was enroute to the scene, I was advised that the collision involved an overturned vehicle as well as possible entrapment. Upon arriving on scene, I observed the collision to be located just north of Kalmia on Conowingo Rd. I observed two vehicles, one a silver Chevy Impala bearing Maryland registration 4EV8224 disabled on the shoulder of the s/b travel lane. The second vehicle, a Mazda SUV had overturned onto its side and was disabled further north of the Chevy. PERSONNAL CONTACT (PHASE 2) I approached the Chevy Impala were I spoke to the driver, Jamie Lee Cotter (10/18/1988 W/M) who was identified by his Pennsylvania drivers license. As I began speaking to Cotter, he appeared disoriented and drowsy. Cotter speech was heavily slurred and he was unable to form coherent statements. As I requested Cotters driver license and registration, I observed him struggle with basic coordination around the vehicle. Cotter stated that he had come from Rock Spring Deli. As Cotter continued to speak with me, I observed his eyes were glassy and bloodshot. I asked Cotter about his drug and medication use that day. I asked Cotter what drugs and/or medications was he taking. Cotter replied he was wasnt taking any medications, but did not initially advise about drug use. As I questioned Cotter further, I observed him become more agitated. Cotter would admit that he smokes Weed but would not provide more details. As I spoke to Cotter, I observed him lacking eye contact. Cotter was not honesty answering my questions. Cotter denied and drug use. As I continued to speak with Cotter, his level of sobriety remained consistent throughout my observations of him. I asked Cotter if he would submit tor SFSTs, he would reply yes. PRE-ARREST SCREENING (PHASE 3) The evaluation took place on the s/b should of Conowingo Rd n/o Kalmia. The surface was wet, on a slight decline and free from obvious debris. Lighting conditions consisted of patrol vehicle head lamps, spot light and my flashlight. Horizontal gaze Nystagmus (0/6 clues) The Horizontal gaze Nystagmus was explained and administered per the NHTSA SFST manual. Cotter had equal pupil size. Resting nystagmus was not observed and Cotter displayed equal tracking. Lack of smooth pursuit not present Distinct and sustained nystagmus at maximum deviation not present margin-left:8px">Onset of nystagmus prior to 45 degrees not present Walk Turn (5/8 clues observed) The Walk Turn was explained and demonstrated per the NHTSA SFST manual. Cotter stated that he understood the instructions and how the test was to be completed. It should be noted that at the completion of this test, Cotter turned away from me and placed his hands in the small of his back indicating being placed under arrest. Instructional Phase: margin-left:8px">Failed to maintain balance 1st Nine Steps: Raises arms for balance Steps off line margin-left:8px">Misses heel to toe 2nd Nine Steps: Raises arms for balance Steps of line margin-left:8px">Misses heel to toe Turn: Completed unsatisfactorily. One Leg Stand (4/4 clues observed) The test was explained and demonstrated per the NHTSA SFST manual. Cotter stated he understood the instructions and how the test was to be completed. Seconds 01-10 Raises arms for balance Sways margin-left:8px">Puts foot down Seconds 11-20 Raises arms for balance Sways Puts foot down margin-left:8px">Hops Seconds 21-30 Raises arms for balance Sways margin-left:8px">Puts foot down Arrest: Based on the following, I had reason to believe that Cotter was operating a vehicle while impaired by drugs. At fault vehicle in head on MVC Slow raspy speech Inability to concentrate Drowsy Disoriented Agitated margin-left:8px">Clues during SFSTs. Due to my observations and based on my training, knowledge and experience as a Maryland State Trooper and certified Drug Recognition Expert, I concluded that Cotter was operating a vehicle while impaired and unable to do so safely. At approximately 2046 hours, I placed Cotter under arrest for DUI/DWI. A preliminary search was conducted on scene. Located in Cotter front right pocket, I observed a green plastic canister. When Cotter observed I had located the canister, he replied O Fuck. Cotter stated that he forgot that was still on his person. The canister contained a wax tab Ice Spice suspected Heroin. Additionally located in a different compartment was a clear rock-like substance, suspected Crystal Methamphetamine. Two buprenorphine and Naloxone strips were also located in Cotters wallet. Cotter was placed in the front seat of my patrol vehicle and he was transported to the Maryland State Police Bel Air Barrack for additional processing. Cotter was read his DR-15 Advice of Rights at approximately 2130 hours. The test of was administered by CPL Brown #4758. At approximately 2140 hours, the result of the test was .00 grams of alcohol per 210 liters of breath. When asked if he would speak to DRE, Cotter declined. All located CDS was seized and processed per department policy on P-334674. Cotter was provided copies of all pertinent paper. Cotters vehicle was towed by Banks towing. An ACRS report was completed in Delta plus. Cotter was advised not to drive for 12 hours. Cotter was released on traffic and criminal citations to his Mother. All events occurred in Harford County, Maryland. Case closed by arrest.
